<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="46" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[280,1777,1638,2589]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">
<taxonomicName box="[326,503,1831,1868]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Choerades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jlavipes">
<emphasis box="[326,355,1832,1868]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[372,503,1831,1868]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">jlavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from a female specimen from Â·Prom. bon. 
<emphasis box="[1531,1578,1831,1868]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">sp</emphasis>
.' (probably Table Mountain, Cape Town) and as my records show the species to be confined to the Cape Province from the Cape Peninsula to the eastern Cape Province I have little doubt that males subsequently identified as 
<taxonomicName box="[1139,1315,1980,2017]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Choerades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jlavipes">
<emphasis box="[1139,1168,1981,2017]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1184,1315,1980,2017]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">jlavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are truly the males of this species. Oldroyd (1974) places 
<taxonomicName authority="Bigot" authorityName="Bigot" authorityYear="1878" box="[836,1278,2031,2068]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Dasythrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrapex">
<emphasis box="[836,1169,2031,2068]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">Dasythrix nigrapex</emphasis>
Bigot
</taxonomicName>
in his list of synonymy but since the type locality of this species is in Natal there is a strong possibility that this species is not the same as 
<taxonomicName box="[744,924,2132,2169]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Choerades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jlavipes">
<emphasis box="[744,773,2132,2168]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[790,929,2132,2169]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">jlavipes.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
I have not seen Bigot's material; if 
<taxonomicName authority="Loew, 1851" authorityName="Bigot" authorityYear="1878" box="[1572,1776,2132,2169]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Dasythrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrapex">
<emphasis box="[1572,1776,2132,2169]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">D. nigrapex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is indeed a 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1851" box="[495,668,2184,2221]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Choerades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[495,668,2184,2221]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">Choerades</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there is the. possibility that it is 
<taxonomicName box="[1269,1515,2184,2221]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Laphria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aureopilosa">
<emphasis box="[1269,1298,2184,2220]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1324,1515,2184,2221]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">aureopilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in which case Bigot's name will have precedence over that of Ricardo.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[280,1777,1638,2589]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">
The male terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[698,800,2285,2322]" captionStart="Figs 1-5" captionStartId="2.[210,272,2476,2508]" captionTargetBox="[255,1619,337,2380]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1-5. Choerades species; dorsal aspect of cr genital bulb 1. C. aureopilosa (Ricardo). 2. C. bella (Loew). 3. C. jlavipes (Weidemann). 4. C. nigrescens (Ricardo) 5. C. serpentina (Bezzi)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1472447/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) of 
<taxonomicName box="[876,1052,2285,2322]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Choerades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jlavipes">
<emphasis box="[876,904,2285,2322]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[921,1052,2285,2322]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">jlavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are illustrated for comparison with other species. Fused gonopodal setae (4 or 5 in number) are short and inwardly directed. Two groups of well-developed setae lie posteriorly of the gonopodaJ setae. The first group contains two setae the second group four.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
